<h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

<p>Use this page to get answers to common questions about blood donation. Your donation can save lives!</p>

<div>
    <p><strong>1. Why is blood donation so important?</strong></p>
    <p>Blood donations are vital to ensure a steady supply for hospitals and emergency care. Every 2 seconds, someone in the world needs blood. Your donation can help save lives in accidents, surgeries, and for patients with chronic conditions.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Who can donate blood?</strong></p>
    <p>Most healthy individuals aged 18-65, weighing at least 110 lbs (50 kg), and without certain medical conditions can donate. A simple health check at the donation center will ensure you're eligible!</p>

    <p><strong>3. How often can I donate blood?</strong></p>
    <p>You can donate whole blood every 56 days, or about every two months. Platelet donations can be made more frequently—up to once every 7 days, depending on local regulations.</p>

    <p><strong>4. Does donating blood hurt?</strong></p>
    <p>The actual donation process is quick and typically only causes a mild, brief discomfort. Most people find it easy and are surprised by how little pain is involved. Plus, it’s totally worth it!</p>

    <p><strong>5. How do I prepare for a blood donation?</strong></p>
    <p>It's simple! Get a good night's sleep, drink plenty of water, and have a healthy meal before donating. Avoid alcohol and caffeine before you donate, and wear sleeves that can be easily rolled up.</p>
</div>

